===Etymology===
{{NL.}} term ''[[anarchia]]'' < {{Gr.}} ''[[αναρχία]]''< &alpha;&nu;(&alpha;), ''an(a)'', "without", and &alpha;&rho;&chi;(&omicron;&sigmaf;), ''arkh(os)'', "ruler, authority".

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈænərki/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|anarchies|-}}

# Absence of [[hierarchy]], [[power]] and [[authority]], complete chaos.
# Absence of any form of political authority or [[government]].
# Political disorder and confusion.
# Absence of any non-chaotic principle, such as a common standard or purpose.
# Without rules or laws (syn: [[anomie]], [[anomy]]).
# A disordered self-government.
# A government without a ruler.

'''Note:'''  As [[w:Anarchism|anarchists]] use it, "anarchy" does not simply imply chaos or [[anomie]], but also an anti-authoritarian society, much like nihilism.  In fact, anarchist conceptions of such a society (such as those of [[w:Anarcho-syndicalism | anarcho-syndicalists]]) often include a low degree of societal structure, namely having complete disorder and chaos.

